# context.md (example)

> This is a sample. Copy it to `context.md` and replace it with a real map of
> YOUR codebase. The planner reads this first to orient itself before touching
> code, so keep it compact and accurate — a stale map produces bad plans.
> Regenerate it only when the architecture materially changes, not every run.

## What this project is

A small client SDK ("Collector") that gathers signals and ships them to a
backend. Public surface is three methods on one class. The example task in
`task.md.example` operates on this surface.

## Layout

```
src/
  core/
    Collector.swift     # the public class: configure(), collect(), conclude()
    Payload.swift       # the data assembled by collect()
    Errors.swift        # public error enum returned across the API boundary
  net/
    Uploader.swift      # batches payloads and POSTs them; retry/backoff here
  util/
    Encoding.swift      # JSON encoding + byte-size helpers
tests/
  CollectorTests.swift  # behavior of configure/collect/conclude
  UploaderTests.swift    # batching + retry behavior
```

## Key components

- **Collector** — the only public type. `configure(options:)` sets up state,
  `collect()` assembles and enqueues a `Payload`, `conclude()` flushes and tears
  down. Treat this class's public signatures as a stability contract.
- **Errors** — the public error enum. Anything thrown across the API boundary
  must be a case here; never leak internal/library errors to callers.
- **Encoding** — has `encodedByteLength(_:)`, the canonical way to measure a
  payload's serialized size. Use it rather than re-measuring.

## Conventions

- Match existing file style; do not reformat untouched code.
- Public API changes are high-risk — avoid unless the task explicitly calls for
  one, and never change an existing public signature silently.
- New error conditions are surfaced as cases on the `Errors` enum.

## How to run tests

```
swift test          # full suite
swift test --filter CollectorTests
```

Tests are the objective gate for the loop; wire this into `--test-command`.

## Gotchas

- `collect()` is on a hot path; avoid extra allocations or synchronous I/O.
- `configure()` may be called more than once by integrators — repeated calls
  must be safe (idempotent), not cumulative.
